<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-288  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 288.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 4 1989 v3 n49 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Feds face buying hassle; agencies caught between computercontracts.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Danca, Richard A.; Brewin, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Civilian and military government agencies are caught without a wayto buy the microcomputers and peripherals they need as a result ofthe expiration of many big contracts, protests of others andothers in the process of being awarded.andP;  The Standard DesktopCompanion contract was awarded by the US Navy to Zenith DataSystems after the earlier contract had expired in Feb 1989, butGovernment Technology Services Inc protested the award.andP;  TheDesktop III contract was awarded by the Air Force to Unisys, butZenith Data Systems protested that award.andP;  Agencies are usingdifferent approaches to acquire the equipment they need in theperiods between large buys, primarily by loading up near the endof a contract.andP;  The Environmental Protection Agency will award aninterim contract to help it acquire the microcomputers it needsuntil a larger award can be processed, which will take over ayear.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government ContractsMicrocomputersMarket AnalysisTrendsCompetitive BiddingUser NeedsNational GovernmentGovernment AgencyEquipment Acquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>